    opt -passes=mem2reg,loop-simplify test.bc -o test_opt.bc
    opt --load-pass-plugin=./build/unifiedpass.so \
        --passes="loop-invariant-code-motion" test_opt.bc -S -o out.ll


2. IMPLEMENTATION SUMMARY
--------------------------

Dominators:
    Implements iterative dataflow to compute dominator sets using BitVector.
    Each block's dominator set is initialized to all blocks, then iteratively
    intersected over predecessors until fixed point. Immediate dominators are
    computed by finding the closest strict dominator. Uses LoopAnalysis via
    FAM.getResult<LoopAnalysis>(F) to identify loops and prints the immediate
    dominator of each block in each loop using BasicBlock::getName().

Dead Code Elimination:
    Uses a mark-and-sweep worklist algorithm. Instructions are initially live
    if they are terminators, debug intrinsics, landing pads, or have side
    effects. Liveness propagates backward through operands. Any instruction
    not marked live with no remaining uses is removed. The process repeats
    until no more instructions can be eliminated.

Loop Invariant Code Motion:
    Processes loops bottom-up (inner first). For each loop, requires a
    preheader (inserted by loop-simplify). Iteratively identifies
    loop-invariant instructions whose operands are all constants, arguments,
    defined outside the loop, or already identified as invariant, and that
    are safe to speculatively execute and do not read memory. All invariants
    are collected in traversal order (preserving dependencies) and hoisted
    to the preheader. Dominator information is computed internally using the
    same bitset algorithm as the Dominators pass.


3. LICM MICROBENCHMARKS
------------------------

Instruction counts measured with:
    lli -stats -force-interpreter file.bc 2>&1 | grep "dynamic instructions"

--- Benchmark 1: Single invariant (x * y hoisted) ---

Code:
    int test(int x, int y) {
        int sum = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < 1000; i++) {
            int t = x * y;  // invariant
            sum += t;
        }
        return sum;
    }

    Before LICM : 7,006 instructions
    After LICM  : 6,007 instructions
    Saved       : 999   (1.17x speedup)

x * y is hoisted once to the preheader, saving one multiply per iteration.

--- Benchmark 2: Two invariants (a + b and b * c hoisted) ---

Code:
    int test(int a, int b, int c) {
        int sum = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < 1000; i++) {
            int x = a + b;  // invariant
            int y = b * c;  // invariant
            sum += x + y + i;
        }
        return sum;
    }

    Before LICM : 10,006 instructions
    After LICM  :  7,009 instructions
    Saved       :  2,997 (1.43x speedup)

Two invariant expressions hoisted, saving 2 instructions per iteration
over 1000 iterations.

--- Benchmark 3: Nested loop (x * 2 hoisted out of inner loop) ---

Code:
    int test(int x) {
        int sum = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < 100; j++) {
                int t = x * 2;  // invariant to both loops
                sum += t + i;
            }
        }
        return sum;
    }

    Before LICM : 80,806 instructions
    After LICM  : 60,907 instructions
    Saved       : 19,899 (1.33x speedup)

x * 2 is invariant to both loops. Hoisting it out of the inner loop saves
one multiply per inner iteration, amounting to 10,000 saves across the
full 100x100 execution.


4. DCE MICROBENCHMARKS
-----------------------

--- Benchmark 1: Unused arithmetic ---

Code:
    int main() {
        int x = 1;
        int a = x + 50;   // never used
        int b = a * 96;   // never used
        return 0;
    }

DCE removes a and b since they have no side effects and their values
are never used in any live computation.

--- Benchmark 2: Dead branch results ---

Code:
    int main(int argc, const char* argv[]) {
        int x = 1;
        int a = x + 50;
        int b = a + 96;
        int c, d;
        if (a > 50) { c = a - 50; d = a * 96; }
        else        { c = a + 50; d = a * 96; }
        int e = 50 - 96;
        int f = e + c;
        return 0;
    }

All intermediate computations are eliminated since return 0 does not
depend on any of them.